Creating a Java utility to split a paragraph of text into chunks with a maximum of 250 tokens can be done using a simple tokenizer. Below is a basic example of how you could implement this utility. This utility assumes that tokens are words separated by spaces.

```java
import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.List;
import java.util.StringTokenizer;

public class TextSplitter {

    public List<String> splitTextIntoChunks(String text, int maxTokens) {
        List<String> chunks = new ArrayList<>();
        StringTokenizer tokenizer = new StringTokenizer(text);
        StringBuilder chunkBuilder = new StringBuilder();
        int tokenCount = 0;

        while (tokenizer.hasMoreTokens()) {
            String token = tokenizer.nextToken();
            // +1 accounts for the space that will be added after the word,
            // except for the first word in the chunk.
            if (tokenCount + (tokenCount > 0 ? 1 : 0) + token.length() > maxTokens && tokenCount > 0) {
                // Finish the current chunk and start a new one.
                chunks.add(chunkBuilder.toString());
                chunkBuilder.setLength(0);
                tokenCount = 0;
            }

            if (tokenCount > 0) {
                chunkBuilder.append(" ");
            }
            chunkBuilder.append(token);
            tokenCount++;
        }

        // Add the last chunk if there is one.
        if (chunkBuilder.length() > 0) {
            chunks.add(chunkBuilder.toString());
        }

        return chunks;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        TextSplitter splitter = new TextSplitter();

        // Sample text to split.
        String text = "Your paragraph or text to be split goes here. "
                    + "The method will split the text into chunks that "
                    + "each have a maximum of 250 tokens.";

        // Split text with 250 token limit.
        List<String> textChunks = splitter.splitTextIntoChunks(text, 250);

        // Output the chunks
        for (String chunk : textChunks) {
            System.out.println(chunk + "\n--\n");
        }
    }

}
```

Keep in mind that "tokens" here are considered as words separated by spaces. If you want to consider punctuation and other types of tokens, you will have to adjust the tokenization logic. The `StringTokenizer` class used in this example is a legacy class but chosen for simplicity. The modern approach would be to use the `split` method of `String` or regex. However, `StringTokenizer` is more memory-efficient for large texts as it doesn't create an array of substrings.

Please make sure you test this code and adjust it accordingly, as it may need to suit the specifics of your input text and the exact definition of a "token" in your context.

If you need to read files with UTF-8 encoding, you'll want to ensure that the Java program specifies UTF-8 when opening the file stream. Here’s an example Java utility method that reads a file with UTF-8 encoding and returns its content as a `String`.

```java
import java.io.BufferedReader;
import java.io.FileInputStream;
import java.io.IOException;
import java.io.InputStreamReader;
import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;

public class UTF8FileReader {

    /**
     * Reads the content of a UTF-8 encoded file and returns it as a String.
     *
     * @param filePath the path to the file
     * @return the content of the file as a String
     * @throws IOException if an I/O error occurs
     */
    public static String readFile(String filePath) throws IOException {
        StringBuilder contentBuilder = new StringBuilder();

        try (FileInputStream fileInputStream = new FileInputStream(filePath);
             InputStreamReader inputStreamReader = new InputStreamReader(fileInputStream, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);
             BufferedReader bufferedReader = new BufferedReader(inputStreamReader)) {

            String line;
            while ((line = bufferedReader.readLine()) != null) {
                contentBuilder.append(line).append("\n");
            }
        }

        return contentBuilder.toString();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            // Note: Replace the filePath variable with an actual file path on your system.
            String filePath = "path/to/your/utf8file.txt";
            String fileContent = readFile(filePath);

            // Output the file content to check if it's correct
            System.out.println(fileContent);
        } catch (IOException e) {
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }
}
```

The `readFile` method in the `UTF8FileReader` class opens the specified file using a `FileInputStream`. An `InputStreamReader` with UTF-8 encoding is wrapped around it to process the bytes as UTF-8 encoded text. That, in turn, is wrapped in a `BufferedReader` to efficiently read text lines from the file. As it reads the file line by line, it builds the content in a `StringBuilder` and returns the whole content as a single `String` by the end of the method.

Remember to replace `"path/to/your/utf8file.txt"` with the actual path to the file you'd like to read. This code also assumes you want to preserve line breaks as they are present in the file, hence the `.append("\n")`. If this behavior is not desired, you can omit the `\n`.

